local processes of socioeconomic development and the livelihoods of local actors. It details how microcredit facilitates de-marginalisation for some, while simultaneously exacerbating the marginalisation of others; and exposes the ways in which microcredit and other top-down development strategies reflect and reinforce the contradictions and paradoxes implicit in rural China's contemporary development landscape.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0https://www.aup.nl/en/publish/open-access  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 4aAsian Studies. 4aDevelopment Studies. 4aEast Asia and North East Asia. 4aEconomics and Finance. 4aPolitics and Government. 4aSociology and Social History. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economics / Microeconomics.2bisacsh  aActor-oriented Approach.  aChina.  aFinancial Inclusion.  aLivelihoods.  aMarginalisation.  aMicrocredit.  aMicrofinance.  aRelational Approach.  aRural Development.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311066152108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Packagez978311064982640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789048544271?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789048544271zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789048544271/original  a978-3-11-064982-6 Asian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Package  a978-3-11-066152-1 Amsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA